WEBVTT

1
00:59:13.153 --> 00:59:20.933
Incoming livestream: Alright, thanks everyone for, the technical difficulties. I really appreciate the AV staff here. I'll just get started, and we'll just, we'll just work with what we got.

2
00:59:20.933 --> 00:59:35.152
Incoming livestream: Hey everyone, thanks for coming to my talk. I'm Matt Maisel, I'm CTO and co-founder of Sendera. We're building trustworthy, agent partners. And I've spent the last 15 years at the intersection of machine learning, security, and software engineering.

3
00:59:37.273 --> 00:59:44.353
Incoming livestream: Today, I'm going to be showing you how we can hook coding agents and adjudicate their actions using the CDER policy language.

4
00:59:44.993 --> 01:00:02.382
Incoming livestream: And if you're in this, track today, there's a lot of good background material. This is a lightning talk, so we're gonna move really fast. We're actually gonna unroll the coding agent loop and build a policy harness all within the next 10 minutes. So, coding agent scaffolds, plan, generate, execute code, and run tools in loops.

5
01:00:02.423 --> 01:00:11.423
Incoming livestream: We can map this action space into the trajectory event model that consists of, five, four, event types, actions, observations, control, and state.

6
01:00:11.523 --> 01:00:19.932
Incoming livestream: Let's say an agent's maybe already working on some coding task, it's had a plan, it's going and generating code, triggering actions. So starting at the bottom left.

7
01:00:19.933 --> 01:00:32.112
Incoming livestream: We have, the agent initiating actions, such as writing or modifying files, running shell commands, executing code, and these actions are all, mutating the environment that that agent's operating in.

8
01:00:32.123 --> 01:00:37.883
Incoming livestream: The environment then emits an observation, back to the agent, providing feedback to the next model inference call.

9
01:00:39.493 --> 01:00:55.003
Incoming livestream: Meanwhile, we also have control events, right, that handle user prompts, permission requests, sub-agent, agent orchestration, and then we have state events that handle, mechanics like memory compaction, pruning, environment snapshots, and so forth.

10
01:00:55.613 --> 01:01:14.203
Incoming livestream: So, with this event model, we can actually take our now-canonical lethal trifecta threat model and map it to these trajectory events, and we can see that this just becomes, untrusted input, right, coming from things like skills, which might be fetched, you know, over web fetch, coming from a marketplace, and returned as an observation, right, as untrusted data, which might have injections.

11
01:01:14.223 --> 01:01:31.102
Incoming livestream: We might already have sensitive data, like source code or internal docs, in the agent context or retrieved from memory. And then, through state changes, right, to make this complete lethal trifecta, we would have, like, shell commands or code execution, right, that would, would lead to exfill of that data.

12
01:01:31.103 --> 01:01:47.373
Incoming livestream: But this is just one narrow threat model, data exfil, and with this trajectory model, we can do, we can do more complex, even multi, multi-step attacks, right, that are, going to have observations and actions over multiple turns of the loop that might involve, control events and state events.

13
01:01:47.683 --> 01:02:04.102
Incoming livestream: And we can also map other threat and risk models, like OWASPOP10 for Agentic applications to this. And this is really just looking, helping us really map where we want to have control over the exact boundaries around these events and where they're produced. And this is where, reference monitors, come in.

14
01:02:04.223 --> 01:02:23.812
Incoming livestream: So, we want a reference monitor sitting outside the agent and the model, right, to mediate every event. Ideally, this monitor is always invoked, it's tamper-proof and verifiable, so it acts as our hard security boundary between the agent control, observation, action, and state events, and where they're, you know, produced by the agent and by the system and the environment.

15
01:02:23.833 --> 01:02:35.442
Incoming livestream: But a reference monitor by itself, it's only as good as the policy enforcement, points that it supports, right, where we can exert our control and where we can hook in. And that's, again, that's where, where agent coding hooks come into play.

16
01:02:36.013 --> 01:02:49.972
Incoming livestream: So hooks allow us to intercept these trajectory events, process them, decide whether to allow, modify, or stop the agent's loop, so we're changing the agent's behavior. And this is invoked at different lifecycle stages of the agent loop.

17
01:02:49.973 --> 01:03:01.082
Incoming livestream: And each coding agent implementation has its own details. Gemini CLI, for example, has before and after model hooks, which lets you stream individual tokens and do processing on them.

18
01:03:01.083 --> 01:03:20.962
Incoming livestream: Cloud Code doesn't, actually have any model hooks at all, other than the final agent response, that's returned as a notification event type. And then Cursor has, pretty granular hook types for MCP, shell commands, as well as more generic tool calls. So with these hook lifecycle events, again, at each of these key event types.

19
01:03:20.963 --> 01:03:27.262
Incoming livestream: We now have a policy, enforcement point. Now we need a way to express policies around this model.

20
01:03:28.033 --> 01:03:40.123
Incoming livestream: So, we're choosing Cedar, in this implementation, to authorize these trajectory events and really the actions of the agent, and we're invoking that, processing and authorizing, whenever each hook event's triggered.

21
01:03:40.123 --> 01:03:58.522
Incoming livestream: So CEDAR is a policy language that's expressive, fast, and analyzable, thanks to its formal properties and use of the lean symbolic compiler. Unlike other policy languages like Rego, CEDAR policies can be analyzed through these formal methods to check for contradictory, vacuous, or other shadow policy subsets.

22
01:03:58.583 --> 01:04:17.952
Incoming livestream: And Cedar also has a nice, support for permission models, like attribute-based access control, which maps nicely, nicely to this domain. So you can see an example of this by looking at this, shell command action and context type in the middle, where we can see different schemas, for the entities, like agent and user and trajectory.

23
01:04:17.953 --> 01:04:33.063
Incoming livestream: And this is where we can add attributes with signature tags, or data sensitivity classifications, and other attributes that might come from safety models or other guardrails that we're using, right, to compute values and compute attributes for these policies.

24
01:04:33.973 --> 01:04:48.063
Incoming livestream: And policies don't just need to be security-oriented, they can also be, for agent behavior. So this is, it turns out, in fact, that Claude Code lets you write files while in plan mode. So we can have policies that look for this type of behavior.

25
01:04:48.063 --> 01:04:56.452
Incoming livestream: And when permission mode is set to plan, in which this is coming that's specific to Claude Code actions, we can check to see if it's planned, we can forbid the right.

26
01:04:56.453 --> 01:05:04.632
Incoming livestream: Unless that it's the actual plan file that it's writing to. So at Sendera, we covered this, actually, in detail in some research that we released yesterday.

27
01:05:04.923 --> 01:05:20.133
Incoming livestream: Finally, we can also source policy content from our agent context itself, so, like, CloudMD or Cursor Rules files, and we can take, some of the, security and permissions intent, right, in these files, and formalize them as Cedar policies.

28
01:05:20.133 --> 01:05:37.712
Incoming livestream: And in this example, we're forbidding the agent from performing shell executions based off of pattern matching on certain commands, destructive commands, or retrieving of certain environment files. So this one, we have our policies. The next step is setting up policy decision points to have our hook events trigger.

29
01:05:37.773 --> 01:05:53.432
Incoming livestream: So let's build up now, part by part, a hook-based harness. So, we have our local adapters, which are commands that are run by the coding agents. They intercept these hook events, over standard in, they transform them into a trajectory event model, and then send them to a local harness service.

30
01:05:53.453 --> 01:06:11.552
Incoming livestream: Inside the harness service, we have our policy, a CDER policy engine that extracts the entities, processes them against, you know, any guardrail, so it's kind of meant to be bring your own guardrail. But currently, we have YARA signatures, information flow control models, and a safety model. And then, from these results, we also update the entity and trajectory stores.

31
01:06:11.553 --> 01:06:15.612
Incoming livestream: For Staple Bookkeeping about information about the entities that we're observing.

32
01:06:16.323 --> 01:06:32.772
Incoming livestream: Writing Cedar policies can be tedious, but again, thanks to its formal properties, we can generate them with models and then verify and analyze them with built-in language tools. So, we can have a policy agent, that helps us author and validate when given policy features and context over MCP tools.

33
01:06:32.983 --> 01:06:40.163
Incoming livestream: So finally now, we have this complete, harness, that's, hook-based. So let's, let's kind of go through a few examples of this.

