01:09:40.563 --> 01:09:45.552
Incoming livestream: So, wrapping us up, because again, this is a rapid tour.

52
01:09:45.563 --> 01:10:01.373
Incoming livestream: First, I'm leaving you today with an open source Cedar policy engine that's integrated with these various coding agent hooks. This is a deterministic policy engine that's outside the model, so, you know, we don't have to simply rely on safeguards or instructions and prompts.

53
01:10:01.423 --> 01:10:17.453
Incoming livestream: This complements, other defense-in-depth systems, like sandboxes or permission systems. Right? Permission systems can induce consent fatigue and have missing context. Sandbox systems might be overly restrictive, and we can get, the trajectory context here in our policy engine.

54
01:10:17.453 --> 01:10:37.252
Incoming livestream: Some challenges, there is a, of course, sort of this Goldilocks policy zone, where we still have to optimize our policies, you know, depending on the context of the agent. So we don't want overly restrictive policies that cripple the utility, and then we also don't want brittle pattern matching on certain signature, certain, destructive commands, as an example, that could invite policy hacking.

55
01:10:37.253 --> 01:10:43.592
Incoming livestream: So this is an area where we have some ongoing research with optimization and, guardrail latency benchmarking.

56
01:10:43.643 --> 01:10:55.213
Incoming livestream: So we also have, policy scalability, right? The policy agent can help us, with the formal tools provided over MCP, with the ability to, do agent-assisted policy generation.

